"The success of Mallin [sic; Jean Malin] may or may not be responsible for the presence at the Club Calais of one Jackie Maye. "At the Club Calais . . . 'I like that one very much,' he said pointing to Jackie Maye. 'That isn't a girl, that's a fellow,' I told him. 'Stop trying to kid me, Sid,' he said. 'I think I know a girl when I see one.' I tried to convince him that Jackie was a male wearing female clothing, but he wouldn't believe me. 'I'll bet it's really a girl,' he went on, 'and she tells you columnists she's a fellow so you'll think she's a good female impersonator."

"At the Club Calais, Jackie Maye, the boy performer, told of a bitter experience he had with a friend. 'I loaned him $50 to buy a tuxedo. I didn't mind the money so much, but the guy doesn't come here any more.' Jackie was very sad. 'I'll never believe another man as long as I live,' he declared."
"Because one night at the Club Calais while Jackie Maye was doing his female impersonation, a certain newspaperman who wasn't wise to it proposed to Jackie."
"Mulrooney okayed Jackie Maye for the Lido Club on condition Jackie wears a Dietrich tuxedo."

"Frances Dunn and Arthur Budd are back at Torch Club, Police Commissioner Mulrooney giving them permission—but Jackie Maye hasn't gotten the official okay yet. It seems strange, but Broadway can't boast of one real hot stay-out-late spot where the crowd gathers."
"has let his hair grow and now has a girlish bob . . . He's still better looking than any of the chorines there."
"Over at the Club Calais there is also a new spring edition featuring Frances Faye's piano thumping and Jackie Maye's new spring gowns."
"receives orchids almost nightly from a society lad."
